Essential skills for a sponsorship career
Successful sponsorship professionals excel in communication, management, and business acumen. They blend these core competencies with a passion for advertising and a knack for building networks in the third sector and beyond.
What does a typical day look like for a sponsorship professional?
A day in sponsorship often involves liaising with advertisers, crafting adverts, and managing brand partnerships. Head of sponsorship roles may focus on strategy, while sponsorship sales managers balance client meetings with administrative work.
How to start a career in sponsorship
Begin your journey with traineeships or entry-level positions in sports administration or as a brand ambassador. Gain experience in charity finance, develop your sales skills, and consider pursuing relevant qualifications in marketing or business.
Different roles in the sponsorship industry
The industry offers diverse opportunities, from commercial leads managing high-value partnerships to field sales executives securing new sponsors. Roles like sporting event manager combine sponsorship expertise with practical event organisation skills.
